title: 7 things to know about today, plus Facebook now top source for news links
text: 7 things to know about today, plus Facebook now top source for news links Aug 20, 2015, 6:57am EDT Industries & Tags Cindy Barth Editor Orlando Business Journal Home of the Day Chris Ratcliffe | Bloomberg Facebook Inc., is bringing more traffic to news sites than Google Inc., new data from Web… more Facebook Inc., is bringing more traffic to news sites than Google Inc. , new data from Web traffic analytics firm Parse.ly shows. Social media referrals (Facebook is the biggest social network) accounted for 43 percent of the traffic to the Parse.ly network of media sites — 400 major news and media outlets that account for 6 billion page views including Wired, The Atlantic, Reuters, Mashable, Slate, Business Insider and others, according to the data first provided to Fortune . Facebook alone accounts for just under 40 percent of the referrals. Google accounted for 38 percent of the digital traffic in the May-July 2015 data, Parse.ly chief technical officer Andrew Montalenti told Fortune. Read more here . And be sure to check out these other Thursday headlines: Florida Fast 100 revealed In case you missed this yesterday, the four Florida Business Journals unveiled the 2015 Florida Fast 100 companies, privately held companies that showed the greatest revenue percentage increase between 2012-2014. Central Florida put 28 companies on the 2015 list. Check out the companies here . As for where the Central Florida companies ranked on this year's list ... you'll have to wait for the Sept. 18 edition of OBJ. Chase's Dosal to oversee Tampa's middle-market commercial banking Congratulations to Michael Dosal , who was named head of Chase's middle-market commercial banking business in Tampa Bay. After joining JPMorgan Chase (NYSE: JPM) in 2009, Dosal established the commercial banking team in Orlando, creating a group of six bankers and numerous support staff. Two years later, he established the team’s presence in Jacksonville, a statement from the bank said. Dosal’s focus is on providing the full range of credit, treasury, capital markets and corporate finance advisory services to companies with $20 million to $500 million in annual sales. GOAA greenlights $471.4M budget for Orlando International The Greater Orlando Aviation Authority on Wednesday approved a preliminary fiscal-year 2016 operating budget of $471 . 4 million for Orlando International Airport — a 5.3 percent increase over the 2015 budget — and $2 . 8 million for Orlando Executive Airport. “The proposed 2016 budget keeps Orlando under the 25 th percentile for cost per enplaned passengers among all major airports in the country. In fact, 2016 is lower than this year,” said Phil Brown, executive director of GOAA. “Airlines look at those numbers, which enables us to attract new airlines, new services and new routes.” The city of Orlando will hold a public hearing on the budget, with the GOAA board voting in September to finalize it. The new budget takes effect Oct. 1. Wells Fargo eyes growth by revving up auto lending With car sales in overdrive, Wells Fargo plans to open more regional offices devoted to providing financing and other banking services to auto dealerships. Auto dealers are enjoying robust sales, as U.S. car sales in July totaled more than 1.5 million, up 5.3 percent from a year ago, the New York Times report s. On a seasonally adjusted annualized basis, car sales were up by more than 1 million cars in July. Wells Fargo told Reuters that the regional offices focused on auto lending allows the bank's credit officers to be closer to their auto-dealer clients and the local economies in which they operate. Read more here . Wells Fargo is the third-largest bank in Central Florida. Trending this morning on Google Business
